isclosed in multiple locations:\n*   **Preamble / Cover Page Summary Table:** Explicitly states the company expects to be a "controlled company" and will rely on exemptions. References the "Management—Controlled Company Exemption" section.\n*   **"Management—Controlled Company Exemption" Section:** This is the primary, detailed disclosure. It lists the specific exemptions being utilized, warns shareholders of reduced protections, and explains the board and committee composition post-offering.\n*   **"Management—Board of Directors and Committees" Section:** Reiterates the controlled-company exemption in the context of describing the composition of the audit committee and the compensation and nominating committee. It notes that the compensation and nominating committee will not be fully independent due to the exemption.\n*   **"Risk Factors" Section:** Contains risk disclosures related to the concentrated voting control and the controlled-company status.\n*   **"Description of Capital Stock" Section:** Explains the dual-class structure (Class A and Class B common stock) that enables the controlled-company status.\n\n### **5. Conditions Related to Maintaining Controlled-Company Status**\nThe status is contingent upon Elon Musk maintaining majority voting power:\n*   The controlled-company designation and right to rely on exemptions continue **for as long as the company qualifies as a "controlled company"**—i.e., as long as more than 50% of the voting power is held by Mr. Musk or another person/group.\n*   **If the company ceases to be a controlled company** (e.g., if Mr. Musk\'s ownership drops below 50% of the voting power), it will be required to **comply with all Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements within the applicable transition periods**.\n\n### **Key Takeaways for Investors**\n*   **Reduced Protections:** Class A shareholders will not have the same governance protections (independent board oversight, fully independent committees) as shareholders in non-controlled companies.\n*   **Significant Concentration of Control:** Mr. Musk\'s control is reinforced by the charter, which states he can only be removed from his board leadership roles by a majority vote of Class B stockholders.\n*   **Transitional Nature:** The controlled-company exemptions are not permanent; they last only as long as the underlying voting control structure persists.',
