    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Risk Factor Disclosures: Controlled-Company Status, Concentrated Voting Control, and Reduced Governance Protections\n\nBased on the provided prospectus excerpts, here is a consolidated summary of the relevant risk factor disclosures and governance provisions:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Concentrated Voting Control by Elon Musk\n\nThe prospectus repeatedly highlights that **upon completion of the offering, Elon Musk will beneficially own a majority of the voting power of the company\'s common stock** through his holdings of Class B common stock. Specifically:\n\n- **Class B common stock carries ten votes per share**; Class A common stock carries **one vote per share**.\n- Mr. Musk will hold approximately **\\_\\_\\_\\_% of the combined voting power** of all outstanding voting common stock (or approximately \\_\\_\\_\\_% if underwriters exercise their option to purchase additional Class A shares in full).\n- Approximately **\\_\\_\\_\\_%** of his voting power is controlled through his ownership of Class B common stock.\n- As the holder of a majority of Class B shares, **Mr. Musk will be able to elect, remove, or fill any vacancy among the Class B Directors** and will "have the power to control the outcome of matters requiring shareholder approval, including election of the board, and our business and affairs."\n- Mr. Musk "will exert significant influence over our business and affairs."\n\n### Key Risk Language:\n\n> *"This will limit or preclude your ability to influence corporate matters and the election of our directors."*\n\n> *"This concentration of voting power will limit or preclude the ability of holders of our Class A common stock, including purchasers of Class A common stock in this offering, to influence corporate matters and the election of our directors."*\n\n> *"Investors may not be able to realize a gain on their investment and could lose all or part of their investment in our Class A common stock."*\n\n---\n\n## 2. Class B Stockholders\' Ability to Elect 51% of the Board\n\nThe charter provides that:\n\n- **Holders of Class B common stock, voting separately as a class, are entitled to elect 51% of the total number of authorized directors** (rounded up to the nearest whole number) — these are designated as **"Class B Directors."**\n- This right persists **"for so long as any shares of Class B common stock remain outstanding."**\n- **Holders of all classes of voting common stock voting together as a single class** elect the remaining directors ("Common Stock Directors").\n- Class B Directors may be **removed with or without cause** by the affirmative vote of holders of at least a majority of the voting power of outstanding Class B shares, voting separately as a class.\n- **Vacancies among Class B Directors** may be filled by the affirmative vote of Class B holders or by remaining Class B Directors — **"and not any other persons."**\n\n### Implications for Board Independence:\n\n- Following the offering, the board will consist of **eight directors**.\n- Initial **Class B Directors**: Elon Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, and Luke Nosek (5 of 8 = 62.5%).\n- Initial **Common Stock Directors**: Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, and Steve Jurvetson (3 of 8 = 37.5%).\n\nThis structure means **minority Class A shareholders can only influence the election of less than half the board**, and even those directors are elected by the combined vote of all classes — where Class B holders, due to their ten-for-one voting ratio, will hold the overwhelming majority of voting power.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Controlled-Company Status and Exemptions\n\nBecause Mr. Musk holds more than 50% of the voting power with respect to director elections, the company **qualifies as a "controlled company"** under both **Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules**.\n\n### Specific Exemptions the Company Will Rely On:\n\nUnder the controlled-company exemption, the company is **not required** to comply with:\n\n- **Board independence requirement**: A majority of the board need not consist of independent directors.\n- **Independent nominating committee**: Director nominees need not be selected or recommended by a nominating committee composed entirely of independent directors.\n- **Independent compensation committee**: The compensation committee need not be composed entirely of independent directors.\n- **Annual committee performance evaluations**: Annual evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees are not required.\n\n### Company\'s Stated Intent:\n\n> *"Following the completion of this offering, we intend to utilize certain of these exemptions. As a result, we do not expect to have a compensation and nominating committee that is composed entirely of independent directors or that has a committee charter that addresses all Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas requirements applicable to companies that are not controlled companies."*\n\n### Warning to Class A Shareholders:\n\n> *"Accordingly, our Class A shareholders will not have the same protections afforded to shareholders of companies that are subject to all of the corporate governance requirements of Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas."*\n\nThe company notes it **will** remain subject to the requirement to have an **audit committee composed entirely of independent directors**.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Protected Leadership Position of Elon Musk\n\nA particularly notable provision is the **charter-based protection of Mr. Musk\'s roles**:\n\n- Mr. Musk will serve as **Chief Executive Officer, Chief Technical Officer, and Chairman of the board**.\n- He **"will only be subject to removal from the board and from his Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the board leadership positions with the approval of the holders of at least a majority of the voting power of the outstanding shares of our Class B common stock, voting separately as a class."**\n\nThis effectively means **Mr. Musk cannot be removed from his leadership positions unless holders of a majority of Class B stock vote for his removal** — and since he holds a majority of Class B stock, this is a self-reinforcing protection.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Class B Share Conversion Mechanics and Long-Term Implications\n\n- **Transfers of Class B shares generally trigger automatic conversion to Class A shares**, subject to limited exceptions (inter-family transfers and transfers to "permitted transferees").\n- This means that **over time, the relative voting power of those Class B holders who retain their shares will increase** as other Class B shares convert.\n\n> *"If Mr. Musk retains a significant portion of his holdings of Class B common stock for an extended period of time, he could continue to control the election and removal of a majority of our board."*\n\n### Risk of Control Transfer:\n\n> *"If Mr. Musk were to sell, transfer or otherwise dispose of a sufficient number of his shares of Class B common stock such that he no longer holds a majority of the outstanding shares of Class B common stock, another holder or group of holders of Class B common stock could obtain the ability to elect and remove a majority of our board and thereby effectively control the Company. Any such change in control could result in changes to our strategic direction, management, business plans or policies that may not be aligned with the interests of holders of our Class A common stock."*\n\n---\n\n## 6. Anti-Takeover Provisions\n\nSeveral charter and bylaw provisions reinforce the concentration of control and have **anti-takeover effects**:\n\n| Provision | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **No cumulative voting** | Charter does not permit cumulative voting in director elections, making it nearly impossible for minority shareholders to elect any directors. |\n| **Special meetings** | May only be called by the chairman, CEO, president (if required by TBOC), the board, **the founder**, or shareholders holding **not less than 50%** of outstanding voting shares. |\n| **Written consent actions** | Require consent of holders of not less than the minimum number of votes that would be necessary to take the action at a meeting. |\n| **Texas Business Organizations Code § 21.606** | Prohibits business combinations with an "affiliated shareholder" for **three years** unless the board approved the combination or the transaction that created the affiliation, or unless approved by two-thirds of disinterested shareholders at a meeting called for that purpose at least six months after the acquisition date. |\n| **No separate class votes (beyond Class B)** | Charter opts out of separate class votes that would otherwise be required under the TBOC for actions such as increasing/decreasing authorized shares, reclassifying shares, or changing par value — **except** for specified Class B protections. |\n\nThe prospectus explicitly acknowledges:\n\n> *"This may have the effect of deferring, delaying or discouraging hostile takeovers, or changes in control or management, of the Company."*\n\n---\n\n## 7. Reduced Protections for Class A Shareholders — Summary\n\nThe prospectus synthesizes the overall risk for Class A investors:\n\n> *"The price of our Class A common stock may not reflect our actual operating performance. Accordingly, investors may not be able to realize a gain on their investment and could lose all or part of their investment in our Class A common stock."*\n\nThe **risk factors section** specifically directs readers:\n\n> *"You should carefully read and consider the information set forth in the section titled \'Risk Factors\' beginning on page 26, together with all of the other information set forth in this prospectus, before deciding whether to invest in our Class A common stock."*\n\nAdditionally, the risk factors address **stock overhang risk** — the potential for sales by existing shareholders under registration rights agreements and Rule 144:\n\n> *"Resales of our Class A common stock by Mr. Musk or other existing shareholders, or the perception that such sales may occur, could cause the market price of our Class A common stock to decline significantly, regardless of our actual business performance."*\n\n---\n\n## In Summary\n\nThe prospectus paints a clear picture of a governance structure designed to **consolidate control in Elon Musk and Class B shareholders**, with the following key implications for Class A public investors:\n\n1. **Virtually no influence** over director elections or corporate matters due to the 10:1 voting ratio and Class B\'s right to elect 51% of directors.\n2. **No ability to remove** Mr. Musk from his CEO, CTO, and Chairman roles without Class B majority approval.\n3. **Reduced corporate governance protections** due to controlled-company exemptions from Nasdaq independence requirements for the board, nominating committee, and compensation committee.\n4. **Significant anti-takeover protections** that further entrench existing management and prevent hostile bids or activist campaigns.\n5. **Concentration risk** — if Mr. Musk\'s interests diverge from those of Class A shareholders, there is no practical mechanism for Class A holders to override his decisions.',
