            'final_result': '\n# SpaceX Nasdaq Controlled-Company Exemptions Analysis\n\n## 1. Board-Level and Committee-Level Independence Requirements WAIVED\n\nSpaceX, as a "controlled company" under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules (because Elon Musk will beneficially own more than 50% of the voting power of the common stock), intends to rely on exemptions from the following four corporate governance requirements:\n\n### Waived Requirements:\n\n| # | Requirement Waived | Level | Description |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Majority Independent Board** | Board | The requirement that a majority of the board of directors consist of independent directors as defined under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules. |\n| 2 | **Independent Nominating Committee** | Committee | The requirement that director nominees be selected or recommended for board selection by a nominating committee composed entirely of independent directors, with a written charter addressing the nominations process. |\n| 3 | **Independent Compensation Committee** | Committee | The requirement that the compensation committee be composed entirely of independent directors, with a written charter addressing the committee\'s purpose and responsibilities. |\n| 4 | **Annual Committee Performance Evaluations** | Committee | The requirement for annual performance evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees. |\n\n### Practical Effect of the Exemptions:\n\nFollowing the offering, SpaceX\'s board will consist of **eight directors** — five Class B Directors (Elon Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, and Luke Nosek) and three Common Stock Directors (Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, and Steve Jurvetson). The combined **compensation and nominating committee** will include Ira Ehrenpreis and Luke Nosek (both described as independent) and Antonio J. Gracias (not described as independent), confirming the company is relying on the exemption from full committee independence. The filing states explicitly:\n\n> *"As a result, we do not expect to have a compensation and nominating committee that is composed entirely of independent directors or that has a committee charter that addresses all Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas requirements applicable to companies that are not controlled companies."*\n\n---\n\n## 2. Requirements That REMAIN FULLY APPLICABLE Regardless of Controlled-Company Status\n\n### One requirement is explicitly preserved:\n\n| Requirement | Level | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Audit Committee Independence** | Committee | The requirement that the audit committee be composed entirely of independent directors. This requirement **cannot be waived** under the controlled-company exemption. |\n\nThe filing states:\n\n> *"As a controlled company, we will remain subject to rules that require us to have an audit committee composed entirely of independent directors."*\n\nSpaceX\'s audit committee will initially consist of **Randy Glein** and **Steve Jurvetson**, both of whom qualify as independent directors for purposes of Rule 10A-3 of the Exchange Act and the listing standards of Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas. Randy Glein is expected to serve as audit committee financial expert. A third independent member will be identified within the applicable one-year period under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Conditionality of the Exemptions on Maintaining Controlled-Company Status\n\n**Yes, the waivers are conditioned on SpaceX maintaining controlled-company status.** The filing makes this explicit:\n\n> *"In the event that we cease to be a \'controlled company\' and our shares continue to be listed on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas, we will be required to comply with all of the applicable governance requirements within the applicable transition periods."*\n\nKey points regarding conditionality:\n\n- **The exemptions are not permanent.** They continue only for as long as more than 50% of the voting power with respect to director elections is held by Elon Musk (or any other person or group).\n- **If Mr. Musk\'s voting power drops below 50%** (e.g., through conversion or transfer of Class B shares to Class A), SpaceX would lose controlled-company status and become subject to **all** Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas governance requirements, including board majority independence, fully independent compensation and nominating committees, and annual committee evaluations.\n- **The filing references "applicable transition periods"** but does not specify their exact length in the prospectus. Under standard Nasdaq rules, phase-in periods for regaining full compliance are typically structured (e.g., one year for audit committee third member, reasonable time for other committees). The only specific timeline disclosed is the **one-year period** to appoint a third independent audit committee member.\n- **Class B shares automatically convert to Class A upon transfer** (with limited exceptions for inter-family and permitted transferee transfers), meaning that over time, Mr. Musk\'s relative voting power may increase as other Class B shares convert, potentially extending the duration of controlled-company status — or conversely, if Mr. Musk himself transfers a sufficient number of Class B shares, controlled-company status could be lost.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Where in the Filing the Specific Exemptions Are Disclosed\n\nThe controlled-company exemptions are disclosed in the following locations:\n\n| Location | Content |\n|---|---|\n| **Cover Page / Prospectus Summary** | States that SpaceX expects to be a "controlled company" and intends to rely on exemptions from certain corporate governance listing requirements. Warns that Class A shareholders "will not have the same protections afforded to shareholders of companies that are subject to all of the corporate governance requirements." Directs readers to "Management—Controlled Company Exemption." |\n| **"Management — Controlled Company Exemption"** | **Primary disclosure section.** Lists each specific exemption being relied upon, identifies the audit committee independence requirement as surviving the exemption, and discloses the transition-period obligation if controlled-company status is lost. |\n| **"Management — Board of Directors and Committees"** | Reiterates the controlled-company exemption in context, specifically noting: *"As a \'controlled company,\' we will rely upon the exemption from Nasdaq\'s and Nasdaq Texas\' requirement that we have a compensation and nominating committee that is composed entirely of independent directors with a committee charter that addresses all Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas\' requirements applicable to companies that are not controlled companies."* Also confirms the audit committee must remain fully independent. |\n| **"Risk Factors"** | Contains risk disclosures related to concentrated voting control, reduced governance protections for Class A shareholders, and the implications of the controlled-company structure. |\n| **"Description of Capital Stock"** | Explains the dual-class structure (Class A: 1 vote/share; Class B: 10 votes/share) and the Class B directors\' right to elect 51% of the board, which is the structural basis for controlled-company status. |\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| Governance Requirement | Waived? | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| Majority independent board | **Yes** | Waived under controlled-company exemption |\n| Independent nominating committee (composition + charter) | **Yes** | Waived under controlled-company exemption |\n| Independent compensation committee (composition + charter) | **Yes** | Waived under controlled-company exemption |\n| Annual committee performance evaluations | **Yes** | Waived under controlled-company exemption |\n| Independent audit committee | **No** | **Mandatory** — remains fully applicable; cannot be waived |\n\nAll waivers are **conditional** on SpaceX continuously maintaining controlled-company status (i.e., Elon Musk retaining more than 50% of voting power). If controlled-company status is lost, SpaceX must achieve full compliance with all Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas governance requirements within the applicable transition periods.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement filed May 20, 2026: https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\n  - Sections referenced: "Management — Controlled Company Exemption," "Management — Board of Directors and Committees," "Risk Factors," "Description of Capital Stock," and Prospectus Summary/Cover Page\n'
